specific one of us or just we as a team can answer them there at the end

00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:48.279
together. So my name is Julia Silgi. I'm an engineering manager here at

00:00:48.279 --> 00:00:53.799
Posit and I've been working on the Positron team for about the last year. So

00:00:53.799 --> 00:01:00.040
Positron is a new next-generation data science IDE. IDE stands for Integrated

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:05.000
Development Environment and it is a piece of software that allows you as a

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.639
user to yourself develop software. So here in this example screenshot somebody

00:01:10.639 --> 00:01:16.440
is writing a report using Cordo and R and there are there are a ton of IDEs

00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:20.519
out there in the world and what we're going to do during this session is tell

00:01:20.639 --> 00:01:26.040
you a little bit about what's new and or different and or special about Positron

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:31.279
so that you can know why we're building this and also maybe more importantly

00:01:31.279 --> 00:01:36.400
whether it might be a good fit for you. The first thing I want to tell you is

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:43.199
that Positron is an IDE for data science. We at Posit have just extensive

00:01:43.199 --> 00:01:48.160
domain knowledge when it comes to data science tooling and we know that someone

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:53.080
who is writing code to analyze data is different in some pretty fundamental

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:57.400
ways from someone who is writing code for general software engineering

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:01.839
purposes like if they're building a website or building a mobile app. So we

00:02:01.839 --> 00:02:08.860
are huge proponents of code first data science as opposed to a GUI tool or like

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:15.399
a no code or a low code solution but it is a fact that tools that are built for

00:02:15.399 --> 00:02:20.320
a typical software engineer who is writing code they're often not a good

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:25.679
fit for someone who is just right he was writing code to analyze data so all

00:02:25.679 --> 00:02:31.720
across our org pretty much every single thing we build or make or do is informed

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:37.080
by how deeply we know this and we believe in this that we can make you as

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:42.279
a data practitioner more productive by building tools that are specific for the

00:02:42.279 --> 00:02:47.199
kinds of tasks that you need to do. So this is exactly why we're building a new

00:02:47.199 --> 00:02:52.639
IDE. There isn't anything quite like Positron out there and we hope that it's

00:02:52.639 --> 00:02:57.320
going to become one platform where you can do all of your data science. The

00:02:57.320 --> 00:03:02.880
second thing I want to tell you is that Positron is a multilingual or polyglot

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:09.460
IDE. Currently as of today it has support for both R and for Python. A lot of

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:13.660
environments that are built for you to do data analysis are specifically built

00:03:13.660 --> 00:03:19.539
just to use one language for scientific computing. So tools that you may have

00:03:19.539 --> 00:03:23.580
heard of or you know you yourself have used that fall into this category

00:03:23.580 --> 00:03:31.100
include RStudio, things like MATLAB, IDEs like Spyder. There's a lot of these and

00:03:31.100 --> 00:03:36.460
there are real limits to these kinds of tools and IDEs especially for the high

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:42.699
and growing proportion of you who use more than one language for your

00:03:42.699 --> 00:03:47.339
data science. You can use more than one language literally on the same project,

00:03:47.339 --> 00:03:52.619
maybe R and Rust. You can use more than one language over the course

