plots pane, and you get this filmstrip across the bottom. Between each plot, you

00:18:53.380 --> 00:18:57.219
can see, you know, where you've come from, what works, what doesn't, as you're trying

00:18:57.219 --> 00:19:04.540
to build the beautiful plot to explain your data to others. Or, if you're someone

00:19:04.540 --> 00:19:08.619
who wants to continue on the same plot object, you can see it automatically

00:19:08.619 --> 00:19:12.819
update in the plots pane. You can see here, like we're adding different colors,

00:19:12.819 --> 00:19:18.339
we're adding different labels, and you can also resize and export your plot

00:19:18.339 --> 00:19:23.020
from the plots pane into a variety of formats. So, you can see we can make it a

00:19:23.020 --> 00:19:31.099
square, and we can export it as a PNG, JPEG, SVG, or PDF. And finally, it's time to

00:19:31.099 --> 00:19:36.219
communicate this with others. So, how can we share the beautiful data science

00:19:36.219 --> 00:19:43.260
artifacts that we're creating to others? We have something called a viewer pane.

00:19:43.260 --> 00:19:46.859
This is also something that might be familiar if you're coming from RStudio,

00:19:46.859 --> 00:19:50.339
and this plays nicely with the VS Code extensions that you might have already

00:19:50.339 --> 00:19:56.380
seen and loved, like the Quarto extension. This is interactive HTML that automatically

00:19:56.380 --> 00:20:01.339
gets populated in the viewer pane. This is a Quarto extension, but there's also Shiny

00:20:01.339 --> 00:20:06.180
extensions. So, when you run your Shiny app, it'll pop up. You can interact with

00:20:06.180 --> 00:20:14.500
this directly in the viewer pane. You can also see other things like APIs,

00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:21.380
like great tables tables, and a variety of other HTML documents. So, Positron is doing

00:20:21.380 --> 00:20:25.900
a little bit of interior decorating in your IDE space. It's adding in new furniture

00:20:25.900 --> 00:20:30.020
and taking out that table that you keep stubbing your toe on. Hopefully,

00:20:30.020 --> 00:20:33.540
this allows you to walk through your data a little bit more fluently and avoid a

00:20:33.540 --> 00:20:38.140
little bit of pain. We make these tools to help you because we know data science

00:20:38.140 --> 00:20:41.939
can be messy business. It comes with its own pain.

00:20:41.939 --> 00:20:45.939
My name is Tom Mock. I'm a product manager for Positron, and I'm excited to talk a

00:20:45.939 --> 00:20:50.140
little bit more deeply about one little area of Positron and how much focus we put

00:20:50.140 --> 00:20:55.900
on the little design principles within it. So, when you first start opening your data,

00:20:55.900 --> 00:20:59.459
you might want something like a data viewer, right? In RStudio, there's a data

00:20:59.459 --> 00:21:04.180
viewer. You can see your grid, or you might be opening things in tools like Excel

00:21:04.180 --> 00:21:08.780
because you want to kind of walk through your data or feel the data or explore

00:21:08.780 --> 00:21:13.420
individual cells as opposed to doing group by operations or summarization.

00:21:13.420 --> 00:21:18.180
So, of course, we built this into Positron and made it available for both Python and R.

00:21:18.180 --> 00:21:22.020
But we didn't want to stop with just a data viewer. So, we've actually built what we

00:21:22.020 --> 00:21:27.099
call a next-generation data explorer. Of course, it still has that data viewer grid

00:21:27.140 --> 00:21:31.140
that people are looking for in terms of individual cells and the interaction of an

00:21:31.140 --> 00:21:36.540
indice, a column, and details about them. But we also have things like a summary

00:21:36.540 --> 00:21:40.699
panel showing you summary statistics that are appropriate for that data, you know,

00:21:40.699 --> 00:21:46.540
measures of central tendency for numeric data or unique values for strings or

00:21:46.540 --> 00:21:51.819
categorical data. There's also missing data and column names there as well as their

00:21:51.819 --> 00:21:56.979
type. And lastly, we also have a persistent filter bar that allows you to create,

00:21:57.020 --> 00:22:01.859
delete, and see the filters you've applied to your data as you're exploring it.

00:22:01.859 --> 00:22:05.459
Now, of course, this is not intended to replace your code-first data science,

00:22:05.459 --> 00:22:09.459
but be used with your in-memory R or Python data frames. So, let's talk a little bit

00:22:09.459 --> 00:22:14.819
about that. For the grid design, it's, again, intended to be this polyglot tool.

00:22:14.819 --> 00:22:21.300
So, it's just as good in R as it is for Python. You can expose these data frames

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:26.339
into the data explorer by calling view in R or Python, and that will then populate it

00:22:26.339 --> 00:22:30.180
into the data explorer or using the workflow that Isabel showed with clicking the

00:22:30.180 --> 00:22:35.300
table button. What this means is that the code that you write in R or Python also

00:22:35.300 --> 00:22:39.699
updates the view in the data explorer. So, here, I overwrite a column and change the

00:22:39.699 --> 00:22:45.939
year from 2013 to 2014, which affects the variable column as well as the summary

00:22:45.939 --> 00:22:49.540
statistics. So, this is reactive to the changes you make in code as you move back

00:22:49.540 --> 00:22:54.500
and forth between them. Beyond that, though, we've tried to make it something

00:22:54.500 --> 00:22:58.900
that's highly scalable. So, again, in this example, I have 31 million rows,

00:22:58.900 --> 00:23:03.699
24 columns, and in real time, I can scroll horizontally or vertically across anything

00:23:03.699 --> 00:23:08.020
in the data frame, and it will kind of instantly load that data. We do a lot of

00:23:08.020 --> 00:23:12.020
clever things with caching, fetching different windows of data to try and make

00:23:12.020 --> 00:23:16.739
it efficient in this way. But we've also sweated a little bit of the small stuff.

00:23:16.739 --> 00:23:20.900
So, things like sorting. It's not just one column. It's multi-sorting. So, you can

00:23:20.900 --> 00:23:24.979
sort multiple columns at a time and show which order you've sorted them in and

00:23:24.979 --> 00:23:29.459
remove different sorting as needed so you can modify your data ephemerally in this

00:23:29.459 --> 00:23:34.420
way. We've used model space fonts in the grid to show you things like nice decimal

00:23:34.420 --> 00:23:38.660
alignment, problematic things like white space, or differentiating simply between

00:23:38.660 --> 00:23:43.939
one, I, and L of various capitalization. And then, lastly, for the grid, we've

00:23:43.939 --> 00:23:47.859
worked really hard on automatic column width so you can fit as much data

00:23:47.859 --> 00:23:51.619
horizontally and vertically as possible as opposed to these really, really wide

00:23:51.619 --> 00:23:56.900
columns when you've got a short variable name and short values. So, the grid's

00:23:56.900 --> 00:24:01.459
great, but what about this filter bar? We've intentionally decided to add a

00:24:01.459 --> 00:24:05.219
filter bar that's outside of the data viewer because it allows you to see the

00:24:05.219 --> 00:24:08.339
filters you've created no matter where you are in your data. You can imagine I

00:24:08.339 --> 00:24:12.500
might have 100 columns or 1,000 columns, and I might forget I made a filter on

00:24:12.500 --> 00:24:17.619
column 1. So, we want you to be able to see them and delete them as needed. But

00:24:17.619 --> 00:24:21.300
you can always quick add a filter, you know, at one specific column and have it

00:24:21.300 --> 00:24:27.300
pre-populate that column name. This also gives us the ability to have more rich

00:24:27.300 --> 00:24:31.380
filtering. So, not just I'm filtering on a single value, but for something like

00:24:31.380 --> 00:24:35.619
strings it contains or starts with, or even a regex that says, like, okay, this

00:24:35.619 --> 00:24:40.660
match. And for numbers, we have typical Boolean numeric operations, less than,

00:24:40.660 --> 00:24:45.619
greater than, or even between two values. So, a lot of power here in how we built

00:24:45.619 --> 00:24:51.060
the filters. And lastly, more closing out, we have the summary panel, which again

00:24:51.060 --> 00:24:55.619
has a lot of different component parts. We have the type. So, as a symbol, we can

00:24:55.619 --> 00:24:58.660
show you the type and the column name. If you double click on the column name,

00:24:58.660 --> 00:25:03.380
it'll instantly move you to that column within the Data Explorer. We show you

00:25:03.380 --> 00:25:07.140
missing data. So, even without having to do an operation, you can see, oh, this

00:25:07.140 --> 00:25:10.739
column is 100% missing, or it's got a few missing values that I can work on.

00:25:11.939 --> 00:25:15.300
And then there's summary statistics here that show you appropriate things for

00:25:15.380 --> 00:25:19.859
strings or numbers or the various different data types. So, this has been a

00:25:19.859 --> 00:25:22.739
quick run through, again, trying to sweat some of the small stuff in terms of

00:25:22.739 --> 00:25:26.339
what the Data Explorer can offer you. We're also working on Sparkline

00:25:26.339 --> 00:25:29.859
histograms and things within the summary panel, and in the future, more direct

00:25:29.859 --> 00:25:33.459
connections with remote databases. And thank you so much for the time.

00:25:34.819 --> 00:25:41.140
Hello. My name is Jonathan. I'm a software architect here at Posit. And over the

00:25:41.140 --> 00:25:46.020
last few talks, we have looked into a lot of Positron's features. Today, I'm

00:25:46.020 --> 00:25:50.500
going to be talking to you a little bit about how Positron works under the

00:25:50.500 --> 00:25:55.939
covers. So, by the end of this talk, you will understand the following. You'll

00:25:55.939 --> 00:26:00.739
understand why we chose to build something new. You'll understand what the

00:26:00.739 --> 00:26:05.859
big pieces of Positron are. And finally, you will understand how they work

00:26:05.859 --> 00:26:12.900
together. So, let me start out with the elephant in the room, which is, why

00:26:12.900 --> 00:26:19.300
didn't you just build something on top of RStudio? So, to answer that question,

00:26:19.300 --> 00:26:23.300
we need to kind of go back to our goal from Positron, which Julia talked about

00:26:23.300 --> 00:26:29.060
a bit. We wanted to make an IDE that was truly multilingual, polyglot IDE,

00:26:29.939 --> 00:26:34.339
that's focused on data science. And I want to focus in a little bit on that

00:26:34.339 --> 00:26:40.979
phrase, polyglot IDE. So, to understand why it's very difficult to build a

00:26:40.979 --> 00:26:46.180
truly polyglot IDE on the foundation of RStudio, you need to understand a

00:26:46.180 --> 00:26:52.500
little bit about how RStudio itself works. So, in RStudio, it's basically a

00:26:52.500 --> 00:26:58.739
two-process system. Everything that is inside the RStudio window comes from

00:26:58.739 --> 00:27:03.780
one process that runs R, all the computations that you do. It also takes

00:27:03.780 --> 00:27:08.020
care of saving files, serving up the HTML UI, and doing everything else.

00:27:09.140 --> 00:27:15.300
This, by the way, is why a lot of RStudio features are slow or don't work well

00:27:15.300 --> 00:27:22.180
while R is busy. The only other piece of RStudio is Electron, which runs as

00:27:22.180 --> 00:27:26.500
the Chrome outside the window. It draws the window frame as well as the UI.

00:27:27.300 --> 00:27:31.380
Here's another view of the same architecture in boxes this time. And this

00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:35.300
can kind of give you an intuition for why it's very difficult to add another

00:27:35.300 --> 00:27:39.939
language subsystem here. There's no place to put it. You can run Python in

00:27:39.939 --> 00:27:45.859
RStudio, but when you do, it has to run inside of R. So, you can see why this

00:27:45.859 --> 00:27:51.780
is a really challenging environment on which to build a truly polyglot data

00:27:51.780 --> 00:27:56.739
science tool. Let's look at the other part of that phrase. We want a polyglot

00:27:56.739 --> 00:28:03.939
IDE that is focused on data science. You know, people love RStudio, but we

00:28:03.939 --> 00:28:08.660
get a lot of comments from people saying things like, you know, I love RStudio.

00:28:08.660 --> 00:28:14.979
RStudio is really great, but. It's really great, but can I please, please pop

00:28:14.979 --> 00:28:20.339
out individual panes? RStudio is really great, but can I please have special

00:28:20.339 --> 00:28:25.459
level control over my themes? You know, could I please, please find files,

00:28:25.699 --> 00:28:29.219
hidden directories? Could I please save and load custom pane layouts? Could I

00:28:29.219 --> 00:28:33.540
please have shortcuts? Could I please have gate stash? Could I please have

00:28:33.540 --> 00:28:35.939
custom BIM key bindings? Could I please have a tree view?

00:28:38.420 --> 00:28:42.020
My goodness, we love all these suggestions, but there's a lot of them,

00:28:42.020 --> 00:28:46.579
right? And these things all have something in common, which is that these

00:28:46.579 --> 00:28:52.420
are not data science features. These are IDE features, right? And so, with every

00:28:52.420 --> 00:28:56.900
release of RStudio, we've had to make tough choices about whether we invest

00:28:56.900 --> 00:29:01.939
in those IDE features or whether we bring data science specific features.

00:29:03.540 --> 00:29:07.300
And that's why we made the difficult decision not to build on the RStudio

00:29:07.300 --> 00:29:09.939
platform when we started the Positron project.

00:29:11.219 --> 00:29:17.699
Positron is a fork of another project called Code OSS. And you can be forgiven

00:29:17.699 --> 00:29:23.219
for not knowing what Code OSS is, but I promise you, you do know what it is,

00:29:23.219 --> 00:29:29.780
because Code OSS is the foundation for a proprietary IDE that almost all of you

00:29:29.780 --> 00:29:32.660
have used, which is called Visual Studio Code.

00:29:33.699 --> 00:29:38.579
We are not the only people to fork Code OSS. Many other companies have forked

00:29:38.579 --> 00:29:43.780
Code OSS to make IDEs that are specific for other purposes. For example, there's

00:29:43.780 --> 00:29:49.859
a company called Cursor that makes an IDE called the Cursor IDE with a lot of

00:29:49.859 --> 00:29:55.300
AI features. So, we are doing something very similar with Positron. We are

00:29:55.300 --> 00:30:00.180
taking the Code OSS foundation and adding data science tools to it.

00:30:01.380 --> 00:30:04.420
And we've already covered this a little bit in the session, but what that looks

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:09.619
like is taking that powerful IDE foundation and adding tools like environment

00:30:09.619 --> 00:30:15.939
selections, plots and visualization pane, a really first-class console, an

00:30:15.939 --> 00:30:18.020
amazing data explorer, and so forth.

00:30:18.739 --> 00:30:24.819
So, this brings me to the second elephant in the room, which is, why isn't

00:30:24.819 --> 00:30:26.819
Positron a VS Code extension?

00:30:27.939 --> 00:30:30.660
So, to answer that question, I've got my good friend Twilight Sparkle here.

00:30:32.579 --> 00:30:37.540
So, Microsoft learned a lot from their experience with other IDEs.

00:30:37.540 --> 00:30:43.219
IDEs like Atom, for example, and Emacs, they allow you to load extensions and

00:30:43.219 --> 00:30:44.979
they become kind of part of the IDE.

00:30:46.739 --> 00:30:50.099
This can lead to a lot of clutter and slowness and instability.

00:30:50.979 --> 00:30:56.660
And so, when Microsoft built Code OSS, they learned to put the extensions in a

00:30:56.660 --> 00:31:00.260
sandbox and run them separately from the IDE.

00:31:01.939 --> 00:31:05.859
The other thing Microsoft learned is that when you give people the ability to do

00:31:05.859 --> 00:31:10.020
anything you want with extensions, they just can't help themselves.

00:31:11.300 --> 00:31:13.060
It is a mess, right?

00:31:13.060 --> 00:31:19.219
And so, Microsoft learned their lesson and Visual Studio Code extensions are

00:31:19.219 --> 00:31:20.339
fairly limited.

00:31:20.339 --> 00:31:22.979
They can't contribute custom UI to the Workbench service.

00:31:23.699 --> 00:31:25.699
They run on that separate sandbox process.

00:31:25.699 --> 00:31:26.339
They're ephemeral.

00:31:26.339 --> 00:31:27.859
They can be restarted at any time.

00:31:29.140 --> 00:31:31.619
They stop running when the browser is closed.

00:31:31.619 --> 00:31:36.020
And finally, probably most importantly for us, they don't make sense as a

00:31:36.020 --> 00:31:38.420
foundation for other extensions, right?

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:43.060
R and Python and these other language packs are extensions to Positron.

00:31:43.939 --> 00:31:47.859
And it's very difficult to build a horizontal layer that provides that

00:31:47.859 --> 00:31:50.819
extensibility when you are yourself running in the sandbox.

00:31:52.579 --> 00:31:56.579
So, finally, let's talk a little bit about how R and Python talk to these

00:31:56.579 --> 00:31:57.540
Positron features.

00:31:58.420 --> 00:32:00.739
So, R and Python are extensions.

00:32:00.739 --> 00:32:02.579
We call them language packs for Positron.

00:32:03.380 --> 00:32:08.979
And they talk to the code OSS features in the same way that most other

00:32:08.979 --> 00:32:10.099
extensions do.

00:32:10.099 --> 00:32:14.420
So, VS Code has an API, which is what allows extensions to contribute things

00:32:14.420 --> 00:32:16.819
like auto-completion and diagnostics.

00:32:17.859 --> 00:32:21.459
So, you've seen a lot of Positron's specific features and we've added a

00:32:21.459 --> 00:32:25.939
separate parallel API that allows the extensions to not only contribute

00:32:26.500 --> 00:32:30.819
code completion and diagnostics, but also plug into our console, our plots

00:32:30.819 --> 00:32:32.099
pane, and the rest of our tools.

00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:38.420
It's important to note, then, that those R and Python sessions live in

00:32:38.420 --> 00:32:39.140
extensions.

00:32:40.020 --> 00:32:44.500
And this is important not only for extensibility, but also for this

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:45.300
reason.

00:32:45.300 --> 00:32:47.140
How many of you have seen this screen before?

00:32:48.099 --> 00:32:48.599
Yeah.

00:32:49.060 --> 00:32:52.500
So, this is what happens when R crashes in RStudio.

00:32:52.500 --> 00:32:55.619
And the reason that it crashes the whole window is because, as we just

00:32:55.619 --> 00:32:58.420
established, that window is itself R.

00:32:58.420 --> 00:32:59.540
Everything is coming from R.

00:33:00.339 --> 00:33:02.979
So, this is what an R crash looks like in RStudio.

00:33:03.699 --> 00:33:07.140
Here is what an R crash looks like in Positron.

00:33:09.060 --> 00:33:09.699
It's nothing.

00:33:11.140 --> 00:33:12.579
It is horribly obliterated.

00:33:13.540 --> 00:33:17.699
You will lose anything you've got in memory because your R process crashed,

00:33:17.699 --> 00:33:20.819
but the rest of the IDE will continue to run very smoothly.

00:33:23.459 --> 00:33:26.500
Now, the final reason that it's really important to have all these things in

00:33:26.500 --> 00:33:30.979
extensions is that this allows Positron to be extended to other languages in

00:33:30.979 --> 00:33:31.859
the future.

00:33:31.859 --> 00:33:35.859
And this is something Julia alluded to really well, which is that we want

00:33:35.859 --> 00:33:39.699
Positron to be a foundation upon which more data science tooling can be built.

00:33:40.260 --> 00:33:46.260
And all of the R and Python code that we have written plugs into a public API

00:33:46.979 --> 00:33:48.500
that anybody can write for.

00:33:49.300 --> 00:33:52.099
So, it's not tightly integrated into the core.

00:33:52.099 --> 00:33:57.619
Everything in the Positron core can be added to by anybody via a public API.

00:34:00.180 --> 00:34:02.819
So, we have Positron and we have these language packs.

00:34:02.819 --> 00:34:06.579
I want to talk for just a minute about how those two things talk to each other.

00:34:07.140 --> 00:34:11.939
So, when we built Positron, we wanted to use standard protocols for standard

00:34:11.939 --> 00:34:12.739
functionality.

00:34:13.540 --> 00:34:17.939
And what that means is that when those R and language subsystems talk to

00:34:17.939 --> 00:34:22.659
Positron, they use protocols that have already been established in the data

00:34:22.659 --> 00:34:23.459
science community.

00:34:24.020 --> 00:34:27.219
When we run an execute code, we are using the Jupyter protocol.

00:34:27.939 --> 00:34:32.260
When we do completion and diagnostics, we're using the language server

00:34:32.260 --> 00:34:32.739
protocol.

00:34:33.379 --> 00:34:42.100
We've only added our own protocols when we have Positron specific features that

00:34:42.100 --> 00:34:42.820
we need to power.

00:34:43.860 --> 00:34:44.739
So, quick recap.

00:34:44.739 --> 00:34:46.179
It is a polyglot IDE.

00:34:46.179 --> 00:34:47.699
It's focused on data science.

00:34:47.699 --> 00:34:49.939
It's a code OSS fork like VS Code is.

00:34:50.820 --> 00:34:54.340
Those extensions live with language features.

00:34:54.340 --> 00:34:57.699
We use existing protocols wherever we can to make it easy for other people to

00:34:57.699 --> 00:34:58.179
plug in.

00:34:58.979 --> 00:35:03.620
And we have a public API that lets anyone add new languages or features.

00:35:03.699 --> 00:35:08.260
Hello, my name is Lionel, and I'm here with my colleague Davis to talk to you

00:35:08.260 --> 00:35:11.219
about ARC, which is a component in Positron.

00:35:13.219 --> 00:35:18.260
So, Davis and I are from the Tide Divers group, and we've been working for a

00:35:18.260 --> 00:35:20.419
number of years on packages like dplyr.

00:35:22.020 --> 00:35:28.419
And for the last year, a bit more than that, we've been working on Positron

00:35:28.419 --> 00:35:32.899
with the mission to make it easier for other people to use Positron.

00:35:34.340 --> 00:35:38.260
To help making R support the best it can be in Positron.

00:35:39.459 --> 00:35:43.939
So, we've seen with Jonathan that Positron is a multilingual IDE.

00:35:45.939 --> 00:35:50.500
And we've seen with Isabel that we've broadened our scope to include Python.

00:35:51.939 --> 00:35:54.899
And so, the question that we want to answer in this talk is, where does that

00:35:54.899 --> 00:35:55.780
leave us with R?

00:35:58.500 --> 00:36:02.979
And the answer is that we wanted to make the R support the most modern it could be,

00:36:02.979 --> 00:36:04.260
and the result is ARC.

00:36:05.939 --> 00:36:11.939
So, when you use R in Positron, ARC is behind most of what's happening.

00:36:12.659 --> 00:36:17.620
So, if you type R code and get some completions, ARC is providing the completions.

00:36:19.219 --> 00:36:22.899
If you need to execute a piece of R code and get some output from R,

00:36:23.860 --> 00:36:25.620
that goes through ARC as well.

00:36:28.179 --> 00:36:32.659
So, what does it take to make a great development experience for R?

00:36:33.939 --> 00:36:37.459
There are three main things that ARC is concerned with.

00:36:37.459 --> 00:36:41.540
First, code execution, so sourcing of script or executing a piece of code.

00:36:42.979 --> 00:36:49.620
Code assistance, so that ranges anything from completions to diagnostics to let you know

00:36:49.620 --> 00:36:52.500
that there might be a problem in your code even before you execute it.

00:36:53.620 --> 00:36:55.139
Or contextual help.

00:36:57.139 --> 00:36:58.739
And the final piece is the debugger.

00:36:58.820 --> 00:37:02.979
We want to make the debugging experience in Positron the least frustrating it can be.

00:37:05.379 --> 00:37:10.260
And each of these areas is backed by a standard protocol,

00:37:10.260 --> 00:37:13.540
and we'll see in this talk why this is important and why it matters.

00:37:14.739 --> 00:37:16.419
And we'll start with execution.

00:37:19.860 --> 00:37:22.340
So, here you have a classic Positron setup.

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:26.580
You have an open R file with a bunch of code.

00:37:26.580 --> 00:37:28.820
You have a console and a plot pane.

00:37:30.340 --> 00:37:32.899
And the user here has created a data frame,

00:37:32.899 --> 00:37:35.860
got some output in a console, and created a plot.

00:37:35.860 --> 00:37:38.419
So, where does ARC fit in this picture?

00:37:40.580 --> 00:37:47.300
So, you can think of code that you execute in Positron as a question that Positron asks to ARC.

00:37:48.659 --> 00:37:53.699
ARC does a bit of magic and then provides an answer back to Positron,

00:37:53.699 --> 00:37:56.340
which is able to display the output in the console.

00:37:57.540 --> 00:38:00.500
The same thing when you create a plot.

00:38:01.139 --> 00:38:04.260
ARC does a bit of magic after getting the question from Positron

00:38:04.260 --> 00:38:06.340
and provides the answer back to Positron.

00:38:09.060 --> 00:38:10.979
So, the question is, how does this work?

00:38:11.860 --> 00:38:16.580
What is the language that ARC and Positron use to communicate with each other?

00:38:19.459 --> 00:38:25.060
And to answer this, we'll take a step back and look at what's going on in the Jupyter world.

00:38:25.860 --> 00:38:28.260
So, here we have a Jupyter notebook.

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:32.899
If you're not familiar with this way of doing data science,

00:38:32.899 --> 00:38:36.179
you have a document made up of cells.

00:38:36.179 --> 00:38:40.580
You can write code in the cells and you execute these cells

00:38:40.580 --> 00:38:42.899
and you get the output included in the document.

00:38:44.179 --> 00:38:47.300
So, this is very popular in the Python community.

00:38:48.260 --> 00:38:52.659
But the thing about Jupyter is that it works with multiple languages.

00:38:52.659 --> 00:38:55.139
It's multilingual, just like Positron.

00:38:56.419 --> 00:38:57.540
And it's even in the name.

00:38:58.100 --> 00:39:02.260
So, if you did not know, Jupyter stands for Julia, Python, and R.

00:39:03.540 --> 00:39:09.939
And so, the way they pull this off is not by implementing support for all these languages.

00:39:11.780 --> 00:39:14.419
They have independent backends called kernels.

00:39:15.060 --> 00:39:19.139
And so, when a Jupyter notebook needs to execute a piece of code,

00:39:19.699 --> 00:39:20.659
it's like a question.

00:39:21.379 --> 00:39:25.139
The kernel gets the question, provides an answer back to the notebook.

00:39:26.899 --> 00:39:32.020
And Jupyter came up with a standard set of questions and answers.

00:39:32.020 --> 00:39:36.500
And in this case, it's an execute request that is asked to the Jupyter kernel

00:39:36.500 --> 00:39:39.699
and the kernel provides an execute response back.

00:39:41.139 --> 00:39:45.620
And that's exactly what we needed to communicate between Positron and Arc.

00:39:46.580 --> 00:39:49.219
And so, Arc is a Jupyter kernel.

00:39:50.020 --> 00:39:53.939
And actually, in this notebook, this is Arc running in the background,

00:39:54.820 --> 00:39:57.139
running the R code for the notebook.

00:39:58.820 --> 00:40:00.500
And so, in Positron, it's the same thing.

00:40:01.060 --> 00:40:02.739
You run a piece of R code.

00:40:02.739 --> 00:40:05.939
This is an execute request from the Jupyter protocol.

00:40:05.939 --> 00:40:08.500
And Arc provides back an execute response.

00:40:10.419 --> 00:40:15.540
And the nice thing about this is that it doesn't have to be a Jupyter notebook.

00:40:15.540 --> 00:40:17.379
It doesn't have to be Positron.

00:40:17.379 --> 00:40:20.979
It can be any project that implements the Jupyter protocol.

00:40:22.580 --> 00:40:27.139
So, a few weeks ago, we were super excited when we've seen that the Z people

00:40:27.939 --> 00:40:33.379
saw this new idea written in Rust that implements many interesting ideas.

00:40:34.260 --> 00:40:37.780
And a few weeks ago, they've implemented support for Jupyter notebooks

00:40:37.780 --> 00:40:41.459
and they made sure that Arc would work great in Z.

00:40:42.340 --> 00:40:45.379
And so, here you have R code running in Z.

00:40:45.379 --> 00:40:46.100
Using Arc.

00:40:46.979 --> 00:40:51.300
And we hope that many more projects will be able to do the same in the future.

00:40:53.699 --> 00:40:57.060
While code execution is certainly a very important part of this,

00:40:57.060 --> 00:41:00.739
it's not the only piece of the puzzle, or not all pieces of the puzzle.

00:41:01.860 --> 00:41:04.899
We also think that it's really important to have fantastic

00:41:04.899 --> 00:41:07.139
code assistance inside of Positron.

00:41:07.780 --> 00:41:12.260
Now, code assistance just means anything that makes it easier for you to write R code.

00:41:12.659 --> 00:41:17.620
That could look like diagnostics, where we analyze all the files in your project

00:41:17.620 --> 00:41:19.620
and can pop up a little tooltip that says,

00:41:19.620 --> 00:41:21.379
hey, we think something's wrong here.

00:41:21.379 --> 00:41:22.419
You might want to take a look.

00:41:24.020 --> 00:41:26.659
Code assistance could also look like a function signature,

00:41:26.659 --> 00:41:28.340
where you're working with SliceMax.

00:41:28.340 --> 00:41:30.820
You don't necessarily need to remember all of the arguments.

00:41:30.820 --> 00:41:33.540
We can pop up a signature and say, here, hey, here's what they are.

00:41:35.939 --> 00:41:38.659
Assistance could also look like jump to definition.

00:41:38.659 --> 00:41:44.899
Jump to definition looks like this, where you can click on SliceMax,

00:41:44.899 --> 00:41:49.219
and that takes you straight through to the definition of the function inside of your project.

00:41:51.060 --> 00:41:54.419
Now, these are features that you might have been familiar with in RStudio,

00:41:54.419 --> 00:41:58.820
but Positron has a number of code assistance features that are unique to it as well.

00:41:59.780 --> 00:42:03.060
One of those is help on hover, which I really like.

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:06.739
It looks like this, where you hover over SliceMax,

00:42:06.739 --> 00:42:10.260
and you get this really great inline documentation immediately.

00:42:11.860 --> 00:42:15.939
This is great whenever you're actually just kind of in the flow state of writing R code.

00:42:15.939 --> 00:42:17.939
You don't necessarily need a whole help pane.

00:42:17.939 --> 00:42:20.820
You just kind of need to quickly remember how something works.

00:42:20.820 --> 00:42:23.540
You hover over it, get what you need to know, and you go back to work.

00:42:26.340 --> 00:42:32.020
Now, these features in Positron work in a very similar way as executing code.

00:42:32.100 --> 00:42:37.139
Code execution worked through the Jupyter protocol.

00:42:37.139 --> 00:42:41.300
It allowed us to ask questions and send back answers,

00:42:41.300 --> 00:42:43.300
and code assistance works in the same way.

00:42:44.179 --> 00:42:49.060
With the Jupyter protocol, that really allowed us to standardize these questions and answers.

00:42:49.620 --> 00:42:53.540
With code assistance, we used the language server protocol,

00:42:53.540 --> 00:42:56.979
which standardizes the questions and answers in a very similar way.

00:42:56.979 --> 00:43:02.739
We ask a hover request of Arc, and Arc can send back a hover response in return.

00:43:04.020 --> 00:43:09.060
The reason that, again, that is so cool is because Arc doesn't care who's on the other side.

00:43:09.060 --> 00:43:11.300
It doesn't care who's asking the question.

00:43:11.300 --> 00:43:15.060
It could be Positron, it could be a Jupyter notebook, it could be some other IDE.

00:43:15.060 --> 00:43:19.139
As long as it implements the other half of the language server protocol, you're in business.

00:43:21.459 --> 00:43:24.419
Over on the right-hand side here, our magic 8-ball, Arc,

00:43:24.419 --> 00:43:28.100
is doing quite a bit of work to actually send back these responses.

00:43:28.899 --> 00:43:33.300
Part of the smarts of Arc is wrapped up in a technology called TreeSitter.

00:43:34.260 --> 00:43:37.300
The only thing you need to know about TreeSitter in this talk

00:43:37.300 --> 00:43:40.500
is that it takes in all of the R code in your project.

00:43:42.100 --> 00:43:47.300
We run it through TreeSitter, and it spits out a structured representation of that code,

00:43:47.300 --> 00:43:49.780
which honestly doesn't even look like R at this point.

00:43:50.419 --> 00:43:54.419
However, we can use that and power all of the assistance features

00:43:54.419 --> 00:43:55.699
that we've been talking about today.

00:43:56.739 --> 00:44:01.139
Now, we think TreeSitter is really cool as a project because it works with any language.

00:44:01.139 --> 00:44:06.739
As long as you have a grammar that teaches TreeSitter how to work with that language,

00:44:07.300 --> 00:44:08.340
then you're good to go.

00:44:09.060 --> 00:44:14.020
The problem was we didn't have an R grammar for TreeSitter, so we had to build one.

00:44:14.899 --> 00:44:18.100
Now, we've built it to work with Arc and Positron,

00:44:18.100 --> 00:44:21.379
but as it turns out, there's actually a lot of community benefits

00:44:21.379 --> 00:44:23.459
to having an R grammar for TreeSitter.

00:44:24.179 --> 00:44:29.300
For example, if you were to bring that R grammar over into Zed or NeoVim

00:44:29.300 --> 00:44:31.379
or other editors that support TreeSitter,

00:44:31.379 --> 00:44:36.179
it can power things like syntax highlighting or indentation immediately over there as well.

00:44:37.540 --> 00:44:40.500
And there's also one other big player that uses TreeSitter.

00:44:42.179 --> 00:44:42.899
It's GitHub.

00:44:44.020 --> 00:44:46.979
If you've been on GitHub in the past couple weeks,

00:44:46.979 --> 00:44:51.300
and you've done a search, say, for case when on dplyr,

00:44:52.100 --> 00:44:57.300
you may have noticed that the search results for R have gotten really, really good.

00:44:58.979 --> 00:45:01.939
In this case, we found a function called case when.

00:45:02.899 --> 00:45:08.419
If you click on that function, it will jump you straight to the definition in the project.

00:45:08.419 --> 00:45:11.620
This is just like jump to definition in Positron itself.

00:45:12.260 --> 00:45:15.379
It's a great way to actually explore a new project

00:45:15.379 --> 00:45:17.060
without having to pull it down completely.

00:45:18.179 --> 00:45:20.500
The reason this works is because behind the scenes,

00:45:20.500 --> 00:45:22.659
GitHub code search uses TreeSitter.

00:45:23.219 --> 00:45:26.340
Now, up until a few weeks ago, this did not work for R

00:45:26.340 --> 00:45:29.540
because there was no R grammar for TreeSitter.

00:45:30.260 --> 00:45:31.060
We built one.

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:35.780
So we were able to work with the team at GitHub on their code search engine

00:45:35.780 --> 00:45:40.580
and get them to incorporate our R grammar into their code search engine.

00:45:40.580 --> 00:45:44.020
And as of a couple weeks ago, it doesn't just work for dplyr.

00:45:44.020 --> 00:45:47.139
It works for all R projects, cost GitHub.

00:45:54.979 --> 00:45:57.540
I have one more thing about Arc that I want to talk about today.

00:45:58.500 --> 00:45:59.379
That's the debugger.

00:46:00.659 --> 00:46:03.219
Now, if you've never used a debugger before,

00:46:03.219 --> 00:46:06.020
you probably have done something like credit debugging.

00:46:06.659 --> 00:46:09.860
That's the idea of sticking in a whole bunch of print statements

00:46:09.860 --> 00:46:12.020
inside of your functions, rerunning it again.

00:46:12.020 --> 00:46:14.020
Hopefully, you get some more information out of it

00:46:14.020 --> 00:46:15.459
and can figure out where the problem is.

00:46:16.260 --> 00:46:18.419
A debugger is one more step beyond that.

00:46:18.419 --> 00:46:21.939
You actually get to step through that code one line at a time,

00:46:22.500 --> 00:46:25.780
stop at any point like we've done here inside of mutate,

00:46:25.780 --> 00:46:28.340
and then kind of investigate the world around you.

00:46:28.340 --> 00:46:30.820
In this case, you could use the debug variables pane

00:46:30.820 --> 00:46:33.139
and see what variables exist at this point in time

00:46:33.139 --> 00:46:34.179
and what their values are.

00:46:35.300 --> 00:46:38.100
It probably won't surprise you to hear at this point

00:46:38.100 --> 00:46:39.780
that we've implemented the debugger

00:46:39.780 --> 00:46:43.379
through just another set of standard questions and answers.

00:46:44.179 --> 00:46:46.820
For example, Positron might ask Arc,

00:46:46.820 --> 00:46:49.860
hey, what variables exist at this point in time?

00:46:49.860 --> 00:46:52.020
Arc sends back a standard answer

00:46:52.020 --> 00:46:54.419
and that populates this variables pane you see here.

00:46:55.699 --> 00:46:58.979
Now, with code execution, we use the Jupyter protocol.

00:46:58.979 --> 00:47:02.179
With code assistance, we use the language server protocol.

00:47:02.179 --> 00:47:05.219
With the debugger, we use a third called the debug adapter.

00:47:05.300 --> 00:47:10.500
Now, I have one demo of the debugger that I'd like to show

00:47:10.500 --> 00:47:12.500
because I think it's super cool.

00:47:12.500 --> 00:47:14.419
This is the most mind-blowing feature.

00:47:18.260 --> 00:47:19.939
So, I'm a tidyverse developer,

00:47:19.939 --> 00:47:21.780
so I work on dplyr quite a bit,

00:47:21.780 --> 00:47:24.020
and that means I debug mutate quite a bit.

00:47:24.580 --> 00:47:27.219
So, for better or worse.

00:47:28.500 --> 00:47:30.739
So, I have gone ahead and set a breakpoint

00:47:30.739 --> 00:47:32.659
deep inside of mutate here.

00:47:32.659 --> 00:47:35.060
We can trigger that breakpoint by running the code.

00:47:35.780 --> 00:47:38.979
That drops us directly inside of mutate.

00:47:38.979 --> 00:47:42.739
We can do a couple of steps here to step through the code.

00:47:42.739 --> 00:47:45.219
You'll see the debug variables pane populates

00:47:45.219 --> 00:47:48.260
and you get your very important variables here and their values.

00:47:49.459 --> 00:47:51.620
But I actually want to talk about where we've stopped.

00:47:52.419 --> 00:47:54.580
We've stopped on a very important place.

00:47:55.219 --> 00:47:59.219
It's the boundary between the R code of dplyr

00:47:59.219 --> 00:48:01.620
and the C++ code of dplyr.

00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:05.699
As tidyverse developers, we write a lot of C and C++

00:48:05.699 --> 00:48:09.459
because we want the tidyverse to feel as fast as possible for you all.

00:48:09.459 --> 00:48:10.739
We know we're not alone.

00:48:10.739 --> 00:48:14.820
We know that you write a lot of packages with rcvp, cpp11,

00:48:14.820 --> 00:48:16.899
because you want your packages to feel fast too.

00:48:17.860 --> 00:48:19.379
But that typically comes with trade-offs.

00:48:19.379 --> 00:48:20.739
While you get performance,

00:48:20.739 --> 00:48:23.459
you end up losing a lot in terms of debuggability.

00:48:23.459 --> 00:48:25.620
You can't step through the code near as easily

00:48:25.620 --> 00:48:27.939
like in RStudio like you can with R,

00:48:28.739 --> 00:48:31.459
and you kind of end up resorting back to print debugging

00:48:31.459 --> 00:48:32.580
like we talked about before.

00:48:33.939 --> 00:48:37.139
However, in Positron, you can do this.

00:48:38.580 --> 00:48:43.939
One more step, and we've stepped directly from the R code of dplyr

00:48:43.939 --> 00:48:46.739
into the C++ code of dplyr.

00:48:47.699 --> 00:48:49.459
This is absolutely insane.

00:48:49.699 --> 00:49:00.580
It's something you've never had before,

00:49:00.580 --> 00:49:02.419
and you have all the same tools available.

00:49:02.419 --> 00:49:03.699
The debug variable is paying.

00:49:03.699 --> 00:49:04.820
You can step through the code.

00:49:04.820 --> 00:49:06.020
You can look at the call stack.

00:49:06.020 --> 00:49:07.620
You have a debug console.

00:49:07.620 --> 00:49:08.820
Everything is just there.

00:49:09.620 --> 00:49:12.260
The way that this works is because on the R side,

00:49:12.260 --> 00:49:14.419
we implemented the debug adapter protocol.

00:49:15.060 --> 00:49:18.899
Someone else has implemented the C side of the debug adapter protocol.

00:49:19.459 --> 00:49:22.739
As they use the same set of standard questions and answers,

00:49:22.739 --> 00:49:24.179
they just work together.

00:49:24.179 --> 00:49:27.219
You can step from R to C and even back,

00:49:27.219 --> 00:49:28.739
and everything just works.

00:49:28.739 --> 00:49:29.620
It's pretty magic.

00:49:30.500 --> 00:49:34.739
That is the power of using the modern and standard tooling inside of R.

00:49:35.540 --> 00:49:36.100
Can you talk?

00:49:36.100 --> 00:49:36.600
Go ahead.

00:49:39.860 --> 00:49:42.979
So Arc knows a lot about R,

00:49:43.540 --> 00:49:48.100
and it does a lot to support the workflow of R users in Positron.

00:49:49.459 --> 00:49:53.300
It does this with standard protocols and technologies.

00:49:54.260 --> 00:49:59.060
We've seen three ways in which using standards like this

00:50:00.020 --> 00:50:02.820
allowed us to contribute to the development of the R code.

00:50:03.540 --> 00:50:07.219
Allowed us to contribute to the community and reach a larger audience.

00:50:08.100 --> 00:50:11.699
So we've seen how R can be used not only in Positron,

00:50:11.699 --> 00:50:13.219
not only in Jupyter Notebooks,

00:50:13.780 --> 00:50:18.020
but in any front-end that implement these protocols like the ZID.

00:50:19.060 --> 00:50:22.739
We've seen how by providing an R grammar for TreeSitter,

00:50:23.300 --> 00:50:28.580
we were able to implement tons of useful features for Arc and Positron,

00:50:28.580 --> 00:50:33.540
but also contribute to other projects like GitHub and all of the users.

00:50:34.500 --> 00:50:39.300
And finally, we've seen how as Thai-diverse developers working with Positron,

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:45.379
we were able to benefit from a C and C++ debugger implemented by another group

00:50:46.179 --> 00:50:50.739
in the same way that our R debugger will benefit other projects.

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:55.379
And so that's the great thing about using these standards

00:50:55.379 --> 00:50:57.780
is that the functionality is not locked in.

00:50:59.540 --> 00:51:02.979
So you can be a Jupyter Notebook user and use Arc

00:51:03.860 --> 00:51:07.540
and benefit from all this functionality in the same way that Positron users are.

00:51:08.659 --> 00:51:10.739
And so on a personal note,

00:51:10.739 --> 00:51:14.899
when I learned that Positron would implement R support in this way,

00:51:14.899 --> 00:51:16.020
I was super excited.

00:51:17.060 --> 00:51:20.820
Because despite having worked for RStudio for a long time now,

00:51:21.699 --> 00:51:22.340
now Posit,

00:51:23.300 --> 00:51:25.780
I've never actually been an RStudio user.

00:51:26.020 --> 00:51:29.540
So when I was a student, I learned to use Emacs.

00:51:29.540 --> 00:51:30.899
And when I joined RStudio,

00:51:31.620 --> 00:51:33.139
this was a tool I was familiar with.

00:51:33.139 --> 00:51:36.100
So I kept using it to develop Thai-diverse packages.

00:51:37.300 --> 00:51:41.939
But I was a bit jealous of my colleagues that were using RStudio

00:51:41.939 --> 00:51:45.060
because obviously the R support is very good in RStudio.

00:51:45.860 --> 00:51:50.260
And completions, for instance, were much better than what I had in Emacs.

00:51:51.300 --> 00:51:52.899
So with Arc,

00:51:53.860 --> 00:51:57.860
I immediately saw that I could write a bit of glue

00:51:58.899 --> 00:52:01.699
and having Emacs talk to Arc

00:52:01.699 --> 00:52:05.939
and finally enjoy the same level of functionality as my colleagues.

00:52:07.379 --> 00:52:09.300
So that's not what happened in the end.

00:52:09.300 --> 00:52:11.219
I switched from Emacs to Positron.

00:52:14.419 --> 00:52:17.379
And with the ecosystem of VS Code extensions,

00:52:17.379 --> 00:52:19.860
I don't miss much from my previous setup.

00:52:20.739 --> 00:52:23.540
So I have everything that I need to do my R work

00:52:23.540 --> 00:52:25.699
and work with other languages in Positron.

00:52:26.659 --> 00:52:29.699
But the point is that I didn't have to switch.

00:52:29.699 --> 00:52:30.979
Like it was a free choice.

00:52:32.500 --> 00:52:36.580
And so while there's still a lot of work to make this a reality,

00:52:36.580 --> 00:52:39.060
that's the promise that we want to deliver with Arc.

00:52:39.620 --> 00:52:44.500
That no matter what tools and environments you're using to do your R work,

00:52:44.500 --> 00:52:46.340
Arc will be there to help with that.

00:52:50.820 --> 00:52:55.379
Thanks for attending the exciting Positron session.

00:52:55.939 --> 00:52:59.780
So you've heard that Davis and Lionel were lent out

00:52:59.780 --> 00:53:02.820
from the Tidyverse team to the Positron team.

00:53:02.820 --> 00:53:06.899
And if you just scooch that little logo away,

00:53:06.899 --> 00:53:10.979
you see that I too am on this very exciting adventure.

00:53:10.979 --> 00:53:15.139
And I have perhaps found it even more exciting than they have.

00:53:16.020 --> 00:53:20.739
And there's at least two sources of excitement, I'll call it,

00:53:20.739 --> 00:53:22.340
or a lot of personal growth.

00:53:22.340 --> 00:53:27.139
So one is having to write in programming languages that are quite new to me,

00:53:27.139 --> 00:53:28.739
and that's pretty stressful.

00:53:28.739 --> 00:53:30.580
So there's been a lot of personal growth,

00:53:30.580 --> 00:53:36.100
but also working in a new IDE feels super uncomfortable.

00:53:36.739 --> 00:53:38.820
And so you're seeing Positron here.

00:53:38.820 --> 00:53:42.100
But so all my work over the past year or so has happened

00:53:42.179 --> 00:53:45.139
either in VS Code or in Positron,

00:53:45.139 --> 00:53:47.379
and that's required a lot of adjustments.

00:53:47.379 --> 00:53:51.540
And as we're all saying, no one needs to make this switch.

00:53:51.540 --> 00:53:53.939
But if you're a longtime RStudio user

00:53:53.939 --> 00:53:57.379
and you want to take Positron out for a test drive,

00:53:57.379 --> 00:53:59.219
I want you to have a good experience.

00:54:00.100 --> 00:54:02.659
So these are going to close with a few tips

00:54:02.659 --> 00:54:05.699
for how to make that test drive as successful as possible.

00:54:06.820 --> 00:54:09.379
So my first tip, which will surprise no one,

00:54:09.860 --> 00:54:14.820
is that I encourage you to work inside a workspace or a folder or a project.

00:54:14.820 --> 00:54:17.939
It's a really important concept in Positron.

00:54:17.939 --> 00:54:21.139
The good news is that really is just a folder.

00:54:21.139 --> 00:54:23.379
You can make it more complicated, but you do not have to.

00:54:24.340 --> 00:54:26.979
Analogous to a project in RStudio.

00:54:27.780 --> 00:54:32.100
And there are many areas of the Positron user interface

00:54:32.100 --> 00:54:36.419
that are warmly encouraging you to open a folder.

00:54:37.300 --> 00:54:42.260
And that allows all sorts of IDEs to turn on cool features for you.

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:44.899
So once you're in a folder, for example,

00:54:44.899 --> 00:54:47.300
your file explorer will come to life.

00:54:47.860 --> 00:54:50.179
In Positron, because this comes from VS Code,

00:54:50.179 --> 00:54:53.540
you can't even browse your files until you open a folder.

00:54:54.179 --> 00:54:59.219
And that'll allow you to see the files and folders inside your workspace.

00:54:59.219 --> 00:55:03.540
And it will also set the working directory for your interpreter,

00:55:03.540 --> 00:55:05.219
whether it's R or Python correctly.

00:55:07.219 --> 00:55:10.979
Another super exciting feature that you saw earlier

00:55:10.979 --> 00:55:13.540
that is truly new for R users

00:55:13.540 --> 00:55:17.060
is it's actually quite easy to have multiple versions of R

00:55:17.620 --> 00:55:20.179
living in harmony on your computer

00:55:20.179 --> 00:55:23.540
and to switch between them with quite a lot of fluidity.

00:55:24.899 --> 00:55:26.659
So you'll be able to access that

00:55:26.659 --> 00:55:29.699
in this interpreter dropdown that we've shown you.

00:55:29.699 --> 00:55:33.379
And if you have Python installed, it will be up there as well.

00:55:33.379 --> 00:55:35.540
But really important for the R users

00:55:35.540 --> 00:55:38.260
is you will have multiple versions of R there

00:55:38.820 --> 00:55:41.300
if you've installed multiple versions.

00:55:41.860 --> 00:55:44.659
And the console will always be reminding you

00:55:44.659 --> 00:55:46.820
which one is currently active.

00:55:46.820 --> 00:55:49.860
So I think in this case, I have R Devel,

00:55:50.419 --> 00:55:53.939
the current release of R and the old release of R.

00:55:55.459 --> 00:55:59.139
And so I want to give a quick shout out to a tool called Rig.

00:55:59.139 --> 00:56:01.860
This is not part of Positron,

00:56:01.860 --> 00:56:05.219
but it's a separate little tool that is newly important,

00:56:06.020 --> 00:56:10.500
because it helps R users manage multiple R installations.

00:56:10.500 --> 00:56:13.300
So it'll help you install multiple versions of R

00:56:13.860 --> 00:56:16.500
and switch between which one you want to have

00:56:16.500 --> 00:56:17.939
as your current default.

00:56:18.820 --> 00:56:21.459
And little known fact,

00:56:21.459 --> 00:56:24.739
this is actually easier to do on Windows than on Mac,

00:56:24.739 --> 00:56:27.139
which is like a first for anything.

00:56:27.139 --> 00:56:30.340
So this is actually especially important for Mac users

00:56:30.340 --> 00:56:32.659
to have multiple versions of R

00:56:32.659 --> 00:56:34.100
that are actually fully functional.

00:56:35.939 --> 00:56:40.580
And the new IDE gives us a chance to pick new defaults.

00:56:41.459 --> 00:56:46.820
So Positron will default into a blank slate lifestyle,

00:56:47.540 --> 00:56:49.459
meaning when you fire it up,

00:56:50.179 --> 00:56:53.699
your workspace is going to be empty by default.

00:56:53.699 --> 00:56:54.739
And when you leave,

00:56:54.739 --> 00:56:56.739
we also aren't going to write that to file.

00:56:56.739 --> 00:56:58.419
You can live differently,

00:57:00.020 --> 00:57:02.100
but we're going to try to help people do this

00:57:02.100 --> 00:57:04.260
because we think it's good

00:57:04.260 --> 00:57:07.219
for the long-term reproducibility of your work.

00:57:08.340 --> 00:57:10.419
Because if you have really important objects,

00:57:10.419 --> 00:57:12.979
you really want to save the code that made them.

00:57:12.979 --> 00:57:15.300
And if you have a really, really important object,

00:57:15.300 --> 00:57:17.300
you want to explicitly write it somewhere

00:57:18.260 --> 00:57:21.300
instead of having it sort of live in your global environment.

00:57:23.219 --> 00:57:26.739
Another really important concept in Positron

00:57:26.739 --> 00:57:28.100
is the command palette.

00:57:28.739 --> 00:57:30.580
RStudio has a command palette,

00:57:31.300 --> 00:57:32.899
but at least as a longtime user,

00:57:32.899 --> 00:57:34.820
it came late enough in the game

00:57:34.820 --> 00:57:36.979
that I personally never started using it,

00:57:38.179 --> 00:57:39.219
as Tom well knows.

00:57:39.860 --> 00:57:44.899
And you really need to use the command palette in Positron,

00:57:44.899 --> 00:57:45.699
I would say.

00:57:45.699 --> 00:57:48.340
So control or command shift P

00:57:49.300 --> 00:57:51.860
will bring up this beautiful, wonderful,

00:57:51.860 --> 00:57:54.340
long menu of commands that you could run

00:57:54.979 --> 00:57:57.459
as a very great fuzzy finder.

00:57:57.459 --> 00:58:00.500
So you just start typing something related

00:58:00.500 --> 00:58:02.100
to what you think you want to do.

00:58:02.100 --> 00:58:04.659
And here I've brought up a whole bunch of commands

00:58:04.659 --> 00:58:06.580
that are super relevant to R.

00:58:07.379 --> 00:58:08.179
And in particular,

00:58:08.179 --> 00:58:11.379
you'll see lots of R package development commands here.

00:58:12.179 --> 00:58:14.739
So a lot of things that you might be used to doing

00:58:14.739 --> 00:58:16.340
in RStudio with a button

00:58:17.060 --> 00:58:18.979
or some highly specialized pane,

00:58:18.979 --> 00:58:19.860
like the build pane,

00:58:20.580 --> 00:58:24.340
are available in the command palette, Positron.

00:58:24.340 --> 00:58:25.060
But they're there,

00:58:25.860 --> 00:58:27.219
but they're not sort of smacking you

00:58:27.219 --> 00:58:28.260
between the eyes as much.

00:58:28.260 --> 00:58:29.699
So you will go look for them here.

00:58:31.379 --> 00:58:33.300
Positron is very customizable.

00:58:34.260 --> 00:58:36.500
So you're probably going to want to work

00:58:36.500 --> 00:58:37.939
on your user settings.

00:58:38.979 --> 00:58:42.580
And if you search in your settings for RStudio,

00:58:42.580 --> 00:58:45.860
there is an optional RStudio key map

00:58:45.860 --> 00:58:48.979
that I think most RStudio users will want to enable.

00:58:48.979 --> 00:58:50.020
So check this box.

00:58:50.739 --> 00:58:54.260
And your usual keyboard shortcuts from RStudio

00:58:54.260 --> 00:58:56.500
will start working and doing the same thing

00:58:57.219 --> 00:58:58.739
inside Positron.

00:59:02.260 --> 00:59:04.179
And another thing you might want to do

00:59:04.179 --> 00:59:06.020
is customize your layout.

00:59:06.580 --> 00:59:08.419
So that's another thing you can access

00:59:10.500 --> 00:59:13.139
from the command palette or from the upper right.

00:59:14.820 --> 00:59:17.060
And you'll be presented with a menu

00:59:17.060 --> 00:59:19.139
of kind of inspiring looking layouts.

00:59:19.139 --> 00:59:22.820
And the top three are all Positron specific.

00:59:22.820 --> 00:59:24.899
And they're layouts we think you might like

00:59:24.899 --> 00:59:26.500
for doing data science work.

00:59:27.219 --> 00:59:30.260
And the very top one, stacked layout,

00:59:30.260 --> 00:59:32.899
is the most reminiscent of the four panes

00:59:32.899 --> 00:59:34.820
you're used to seeing in RStudio.

00:59:36.820 --> 00:59:38.739
So the last thing I want to talk about

00:59:38.739 --> 00:59:41.699
is this activity bar on the left.

00:59:41.699 --> 00:59:44.979
And I want to demystify a few of the icons there.

00:59:44.979 --> 00:59:47.300
So the one with a lot of little boxes

00:59:47.300 --> 00:59:49.860
is how you get insight into your extensions.

00:59:50.500 --> 00:59:51.780
So you might go there at first

00:59:51.780 --> 00:59:52.899
and you either don't see anything

00:59:52.899 --> 00:59:54.419
or you're being invited to search

00:59:54.419 --> 00:59:56.260
for extensions you might like.

00:59:56.260 --> 00:59:58.419
And it allows you to install extensions

00:59:58.419 --> 01:00:00.820
from the open VSX registry.

01:00:01.860 --> 01:00:03.139
And this gets at the thing

01:00:03.139 --> 01:00:04.899
that Jonathan was talking about.

01:00:04.899 --> 01:00:06.020
There's lots of capabilities

01:00:06.020 --> 01:00:07.780
you might want to add to Positron

01:00:07.780 --> 01:00:10.020
that don't have anything to do with data science.

01:00:10.020 --> 01:00:11.939
So I love rainbow indentation.

01:00:12.659 --> 01:00:16.580
And so I have this rainbow indent extension.

01:00:16.580 --> 01:00:18.739
And this is a sampling of the kind of extensions

01:00:18.739 --> 01:00:20.820
I tend to have enabled in Positron.

01:00:22.580 --> 01:00:26.340
Right below that is this little flask.

01:00:26.340 --> 01:00:29.860
So if your current workspace is an R package

01:00:29.860 --> 01:00:31.620
that uses TestFat,

01:00:31.620 --> 01:00:33.459
this will open a test explorer.

01:00:34.179 --> 01:00:36.179
I don't think many people have discovered this.

01:00:36.179 --> 01:00:38.899
So this is like a little Easter egg.

01:00:38.899 --> 01:00:40.659
It will give you insight.

01:00:40.659 --> 01:00:42.820
It'll show all of your test files,

01:00:42.820 --> 01:00:45.139
all the individual test cases within them.

01:00:45.699 --> 01:00:46.899
Helps you to navigate.

01:00:47.459 --> 01:00:49.219
You can execute them one at a time

01:00:49.219 --> 01:00:50.419
by clicking on them.

01:00:51.139 --> 01:00:54.419
And you have a little icon that's green or red

01:00:54.419 --> 01:00:58.020
showing you the current passing versus failing status.

01:01:00.500 --> 01:01:03.060
So seven of us got the pleasure

01:01:03.060 --> 01:01:05.060
of giving these talks to you today.

01:01:05.060 --> 01:01:06.899
But I want to make sure that you know

01:01:06.899 --> 01:01:10.260
this is a product of a much larger team.

01:01:10.260 --> 01:01:13.459
So these are all the people past and current

01:01:13.459 --> 01:01:15.620
who have contributed to get us to the point

01:01:15.620 --> 01:01:17.860
where Positron is today.

01:01:17.860 --> 01:01:19.459
So I want you to see their names.

01:01:19.459 --> 01:01:20.899
I want you to see their faces.

01:01:20.899 --> 01:01:22.500
And we would all like to acknowledge

01:01:22.500 --> 01:01:23.620
everything they have done.

01:01:35.219 --> 01:01:37.300
And that's the end of both my talk

01:01:37.300 --> 01:01:38.580
and this whole session.

01:01:38.580 --> 01:01:41.139
So we will have a chance for questions.

01:01:41.699 --> 01:01:44.100
If you want to install Positron

01:01:45.379 --> 01:01:48.820
with this sort of beta mood we have here,

01:01:48.979 --> 01:01:51.459
you still need to go to a GitHub repository,

01:01:51.459 --> 01:01:52.979
which is this one up here.

01:01:52.979 --> 01:01:55.060
I would go straight to the wiki,

01:01:55.620 --> 01:01:58.419
which will give you actual installation instructions.

01:01:59.060 --> 01:02:00.899
And then we really look forward

01:02:00.899 --> 01:02:02.899
to having you take it out for a test drive

01:02:03.459 --> 01:02:05.860
and give us feedback on what's missing,

01:02:05.860 --> 01:02:07.060
what's working great.

01:02:07.060 --> 01:02:08.580
And we can't wait to hear from you.

01:02:09.219 --> 01:02:09.540
Thanks.

01:02:19.780 --> 01:02:20.659
Testing.

01:02:20.659 --> 01:02:21.300
There we go.

01:02:21.300 --> 01:02:22.340
Thank you so much for that.

01:02:22.340 --> 01:02:24.419
I am so excited for Positron personally.

01:02:25.459 --> 01:02:26.899
I have a few questions for you.

01:02:26.899 --> 01:02:27.860
And I'm going to try and batch

01:02:27.860 --> 01:02:29.459
some of the questions together.

01:02:29.459 --> 01:02:31.459
So if I don't get your exact questions, sorry.

01:02:32.500 --> 01:02:34.419
What is Positron still missing today

01:02:34.419 --> 01:02:36.580
that currently is supported in RStudio?

01:02:36.580 --> 01:02:39.060
Why would someone want to wait to adopt Positron?

01:02:39.780 --> 01:02:40.899
I'll give one answer.

01:02:41.620 --> 01:02:43.780
One thing that is not yet implemented

01:02:43.780 --> 01:02:48.580
is inline output in Cordo files

01:02:48.659 --> 01:02:54.020
and some of the complete affordances

01:02:54.020 --> 01:02:55.300
around R Markdown.

01:02:55.300 --> 01:02:59.379
So the Positron leans on the Cordo extension

01:02:59.379 --> 01:03:02.100
for this kind of work,

01:03:02.100 --> 01:03:03.620
whether you're writing Cordo files

01:03:03.620 --> 01:03:04.580
or R Markdown files.

01:03:05.620 --> 01:03:07.459
So a lot of functionality is there

01:03:07.459 --> 01:03:09.459
and will really get you off to a good start.

01:03:09.459 --> 01:03:12.179
But if you have really advanced use cases

01:03:12.179 --> 01:03:14.179
or very specific preferences

01:03:14.179 --> 01:03:16.739
in terms of how your code is executed,

01:03:16.739 --> 01:03:17.620
that might be something

01:03:17.620 --> 01:03:19.699
to stick with RStudio for.

01:03:19.699 --> 01:03:20.580
So there's something else

01:03:20.580 --> 01:03:22.979
we should add to that list, R Cordo.

01:03:26.979 --> 01:03:27.860
That'd be a big one.

01:03:27.860 --> 01:03:28.899
That'd be a big one right now.

01:03:28.899 --> 01:03:31.219
Thank you.

01:03:32.899 --> 01:03:34.580
Are all VS Code extensions

01:03:34.580 --> 01:03:36.179
compatible with Positron?

01:03:36.179 --> 01:03:37.699
What is OpenVSX?

01:03:37.699 --> 01:03:40.260
And especially, can I use GitHub Copilot?

01:03:41.219 --> 01:03:41.620
Perfect.

01:03:41.620 --> 01:03:41.860
Yeah.

01:03:41.860 --> 01:03:43.699
So Positron uses

01:03:43.699 --> 01:03:47.060
a extension marketplace called OpenVSX.

01:03:47.060 --> 01:03:50.739
OpenVSX is a vendor neutral repository

01:03:50.739 --> 01:03:52.820
of VS Code compatible extensions.

01:03:52.820 --> 01:03:54.659
So Cursor uses that,

01:03:54.659 --> 01:03:56.500
Positron, VS Codium,

01:03:56.500 --> 01:03:58.659
a bunch of different forks

01:03:58.659 --> 01:04:00.659
that are maintained of Cordo SS.

01:04:01.379 --> 01:04:03.060
There are some notable kind of,

01:04:04.179 --> 01:04:05.860
I guess, extensions that people ask about.

01:04:05.860 --> 01:04:07.459
I think someone actually just said Copilot.

01:04:08.020 --> 01:04:09.219
So GitHub Copilot is one

01:04:09.219 --> 01:04:10.500
that's not available on there,

01:04:10.500 --> 01:04:11.939
although there are, I think,

01:04:11.939 --> 01:04:14.020
10 or 11 other providers

01:04:14.020 --> 01:04:15.860
of generative AI LLMs.

01:04:16.659 --> 01:04:17.780
And Jenny was actually using

01:04:17.780 --> 01:04:19.540
Continue if I saw.

01:04:19.540 --> 01:04:20.179
Okay.

01:04:20.179 --> 01:04:22.820
Continue is actually a local model use.

01:04:22.820 --> 01:04:24.260
So you could use like Ollama

01:04:24.260 --> 01:04:26.340
to run a generative AI tool

01:04:26.340 --> 01:04:27.939
locally on your laptop or your machine,

01:04:28.500 --> 01:04:29.300
pay nobody,

01:04:29.300 --> 01:04:31.139
and never kind of like send your data out.

01:04:31.139 --> 01:04:32.500
So there's some good options there.

01:04:34.739 --> 01:04:35.139
Thank you.

01:04:35.699 --> 01:04:37.459
What is the timeline for Positron

01:04:37.459 --> 01:04:39.379
on Workbench or PositCloud?

01:04:40.340 --> 01:04:42.820
Soon on Workbench.

01:04:42.820 --> 01:04:44.179
So I'm also the product manager

01:04:44.179 --> 01:04:45.139
for Posit Workbench.

01:04:45.139 --> 01:04:46.659
We're actively working

01:04:46.659 --> 01:04:48.979
on Positron sessions there.

01:04:48.979 --> 01:04:50.179
Jonathan is actually going to be

01:04:50.179 --> 01:04:51.219
doing a lot of work

01:04:51.219 --> 01:04:52.739
along with a few other devs

01:04:52.739 --> 01:04:53.780
on the Positron team

01:04:53.780 --> 01:04:54.739
for integrating that

01:04:54.739 --> 01:04:55.939
along with the Workbench team.

01:04:56.659 --> 01:04:57.699
So stay tuned.

01:04:57.699 --> 01:04:59.219
It will still be in preview

01:04:59.219 --> 01:05:00.820
on Workbench planned for this year,

01:05:01.780 --> 01:05:02.899
but we'd love to hear feedback

01:05:02.899 --> 01:05:03.860
about when it's there.

01:05:05.780 --> 01:05:06.260
Thank you.

01:05:10.179 --> 01:05:11.139
Will there be push button

01:05:11.139 --> 01:05:12.419
deployment to Posit Connect

01:05:12.419 --> 01:05:13.939
for Shiny apps documents

01:05:13.939 --> 01:05:15.379
like there is for RStudio?

01:05:15.379 --> 01:05:17.060
And actually, I'm going to take this one

01:05:17.060 --> 01:05:18.979
because a team that I am on

01:05:18.979 --> 01:05:19.780
is working on that.

01:05:19.780 --> 01:05:20.739
So yes, there will be.

01:05:20.739 --> 01:05:22.100
It's actually available in beta.

01:05:22.100 --> 01:05:24.500
You can go to the OpenVSX marketplace.

01:05:24.500 --> 01:05:26.020
You can use it in both VS Code

01:05:26.020 --> 01:05:27.300
and Positron.

01:05:27.300 --> 01:05:27.860
Try it out.

01:05:27.860 --> 01:05:28.979
We'd love to hear your feedback.

01:05:29.540 --> 01:05:30.820
Yeah, so it's in an extension,

01:05:30.820 --> 01:05:31.860
which really highlights

01:05:31.860 --> 01:05:32.739
like the value,

01:05:32.739 --> 01:05:35.219
like why some of these choices

01:05:35.219 --> 01:05:36.340
we made are just paying off

01:05:36.340 --> 01:05:37.139
in some great ways,

01:05:37.139 --> 01:05:38.260
like the Cordo extension,

01:05:38.260 --> 01:05:39.139
the Shiny extension,

01:05:39.139 --> 01:05:40.500
the Publisher extension.

01:05:40.500 --> 01:05:43.300
Like by making some of these choices,

01:05:43.300 --> 01:05:44.100
we're really happy

01:05:44.100 --> 01:05:45.139
with the user experience

01:05:45.139 --> 01:05:46.500
that is starting to grow up around this.

01:05:48.260 --> 01:05:48.760
Awesome.

01:05:50.100 --> 01:05:51.540
Let's get to some later ones.

01:05:52.179 --> 01:05:53.139
Is there a dark theme?

01:05:54.580 --> 01:05:55.080
Yes.

01:05:55.699 --> 01:05:57.860
Well, OK, yes, but also you can,

01:05:57.860 --> 01:05:59.939
like there's one zillion extensions

01:05:59.939 --> 01:06:01.620
for themes so you can.

01:06:01.620 --> 01:06:02.739
There are, I think,

01:06:02.739 --> 01:06:04.659
three built-in themes to Positron,

01:06:04.659 --> 01:06:06.179
but you can make,

01:06:06.179 --> 01:06:08.500
you can bling out your IDE

01:06:08.500 --> 01:06:10.899
like Isabelle's is always like Barbie Pink

01:06:10.899 --> 01:06:12.419
and what some of our co-workers

01:06:12.419 --> 01:06:13.300
add little extensions

01:06:13.300 --> 01:06:15.379
where like pets are running around

01:06:15.379 --> 01:06:15.939
on the bottom,

01:06:15.939 --> 01:06:17.459
like little animals are animated.

01:06:17.459 --> 01:06:19.060
Like because we,

01:06:19.060 --> 01:06:20.979
these extensions are available,

01:06:20.979 --> 01:06:22.659
your ability to customize

01:06:22.659 --> 01:06:26.260
what it looks like is very new.

01:06:26.260 --> 01:06:28.179
For as you are coming from our studio,

01:06:28.179 --> 01:06:29.300
the extensibility

01:06:29.300 --> 01:06:32.100
and customizability is extremely high.

01:06:34.260 --> 01:06:35.540
How does Positron handle

01:06:35.540 --> 01:06:36.820
larger than memory data?

01:06:36.820 --> 01:06:37.300
For example,

01:06:37.300 --> 01:06:38.500
does it still try and compute

01:06:38.500 --> 01:06:40.580
potentially expensive summary statistics

01:06:40.580 --> 01:06:42.020
like the number of unique values?

01:06:43.300 --> 01:06:44.820
If you're asking about the Data Explorer

01:06:44.820 --> 01:06:45.540
specifically,

01:06:45.540 --> 01:06:47.219
there are some built-in guardrails,

01:06:47.219 --> 01:06:49.060
but again, it's kind of the idea

01:06:49.060 --> 01:06:50.580
of the Data Explorer works

01:06:50.580 --> 01:06:52.260
with in-memory data already.

01:06:52.899 --> 01:06:54.419
There's some long-term stuff

01:06:54.419 --> 01:06:56.260
we'd love to do with DuckDB

01:06:56.260 --> 01:06:57.620
on predicate pushdown,

01:06:57.620 --> 01:06:59.459
basically doing some of the Data Explorer

01:06:59.459 --> 01:07:01.939
things with on disk out of memory data,

01:07:01.939 --> 01:07:03.699
but that doesn't exist today.

01:07:03.699 --> 01:07:04.979
For R and Python,

01:07:04.979 --> 01:07:06.340
it would be the same story of

01:07:06.340 --> 01:07:08.100
there are tools like Arrow,

01:07:08.100 --> 01:07:10.820
DuckDB, databases in general,

01:07:10.820 --> 01:07:12.899
where you can make queries in R or Python

01:07:12.899 --> 01:07:14.899
that communicate with an external resource

01:07:14.899 --> 01:07:15.780
or on disk data.

01:07:17.780 --> 01:07:19.860
If you are debugging a reticulate package,

01:07:19.860 --> 01:07:20.979
does the arc debugger

01:07:20.979 --> 01:07:22.419
step through the Python code?

01:07:22.419 --> 01:07:24.340
Will it step into Cython parts as well?

01:07:26.260 --> 01:07:26.760
No.

01:07:29.379 --> 01:07:30.739
We thought a little bit about that,

01:07:30.739 --> 01:07:32.820
but we are also not sure

01:07:32.820 --> 01:07:34.260
there will be a lot of use cases,

01:07:34.260 --> 01:07:35.459
but that's certainly something

01:07:35.459 --> 01:07:37.540
that we could look into if there were.

01:07:38.500 --> 01:07:40.100
We do have some issues open

01:07:40.100 --> 01:07:43.300
about like increased reticulate support.

01:07:43.300 --> 01:07:45.939
So if that's a particular interest of yours,

01:07:45.939 --> 01:07:46.979
you know, search through,

01:07:46.979 --> 01:07:47.860
find those issues,

01:07:47.860 --> 01:07:49.620
add info about your use case,

01:07:49.620 --> 01:07:50.340
thumbs up,

01:07:50.340 --> 01:07:51.699
so that we can prioritize

01:07:52.500 --> 01:07:54.100
increased support for particular

01:07:54.100 --> 01:07:55.379
reticulate use cases

01:07:55.379 --> 01:07:56.899
versus other stuff that's on our plate.

01:07:58.820 --> 01:08:00.179
Is it correct that RStudio

01:08:00.179 --> 01:08:01.860
will be maintained going forward

01:08:01.860 --> 01:08:04.419
and there will not be

01:08:04.419 --> 01:08:06.500
focus on new features or both?

01:08:07.219 --> 01:08:09.060
Well, I mean, RStudio has some got

01:08:09.060 --> 01:08:10.659
some great new features lately.

01:08:10.659 --> 01:08:11.459
Tom, you'll be a great one

01:08:11.459 --> 01:08:12.820
to speak to this in detail.

01:08:12.820 --> 01:08:14.739
Yeah, luckily, Kevin was the person

01:08:14.739 --> 01:08:16.180
kind of keeping us all on time.

01:08:16.180 --> 01:08:18.500
So Kevin and Gary, Ron and a few others

01:08:18.500 --> 01:08:21.140
are still working on the RStudio IDE team.

01:08:21.140 --> 01:08:22.819
So you can imagine that this is, again,

01:08:22.819 --> 01:08:24.819
an expansion of our focus

01:08:24.819 --> 01:08:26.339
where we have a brand new team

01:08:26.339 --> 01:08:27.859
working on the new IDE

01:08:27.859 --> 01:08:29.540
and then another team working on RStudio.

01:08:29.540 --> 01:08:30.660
So committed to maintaining

01:08:30.660 --> 01:08:32.339
and improving RStudio.

01:08:33.060 --> 01:08:34.339
Some of the feature requests

01:08:34.339 --> 01:08:35.379
that Jonathan highlighted

01:08:35.379 --> 01:08:37.379
that are like theoretically

01:08:37.379 --> 01:08:38.899
impossible to do in RStudio.

01:08:38.899 --> 01:08:40.660
Some of those might come to Positron,

01:08:40.660 --> 01:08:42.580
but this is not kind of

01:08:43.220 --> 01:08:44.500
the end of RStudio

01:08:44.500 --> 01:08:46.259
as much as like there's a new project

01:08:46.259 --> 01:08:47.299
that's working in parallel.

01:08:49.379 --> 01:08:49.879
Thank you.

01:08:50.580 --> 01:08:52.740
How is the Git pane compared to RStudio?

01:08:53.700 --> 01:08:54.660
That's a great question.

01:08:54.660 --> 01:08:55.540
It's been, I'll be,

01:08:55.540 --> 01:08:56.899
I'll be totally honest with you.

01:08:56.899 --> 01:08:58.339
It's been a little divisive.

01:08:58.339 --> 01:09:01.060
I prefer the Git experience

01:09:01.060 --> 01:09:03.060
in Positron because it's,

01:09:03.060 --> 01:09:05.140
it is, it inherits from VS Code.

01:09:05.140 --> 01:09:06.899
But for some folks who have come

01:09:06.899 --> 01:09:08.500
from RStudio for a long time,

01:09:08.500 --> 01:09:10.580
it has taken a little bit of an adjustment.

01:09:10.580 --> 01:09:12.020
Do you want to speak to it at all, Jenny?

01:09:12.020 --> 01:09:13.060
Like the adjustment or?

01:09:15.060 --> 01:09:16.660
People just want me to, you know,

01:09:16.660 --> 01:09:17.859
threaten to burn a computer down.

01:09:18.419 --> 01:09:20.419
I do use the Git functionality

01:09:20.419 --> 01:09:22.740
a little bit in Positron,

01:09:22.740 --> 01:09:25.540
but I did love the Git functionality

01:09:25.540 --> 01:09:27.220
in RStudio more.

01:09:27.859 --> 01:09:29.459
So I just find that I usually

01:09:29.459 --> 01:09:30.899
have another client running.

01:09:31.939 --> 01:09:33.220
So, no.

01:09:33.220 --> 01:09:33.720
Okay.

01:09:34.339 --> 01:09:35.620
See, the license man,

01:09:35.620 --> 01:09:36.979
I'm on the other side of this.

01:09:36.979 --> 01:09:38.419
Like RStudio is good,

01:09:38.419 --> 01:09:40.100
but like Positron is amazing.

01:09:40.100 --> 01:09:41.939
I completely changed the way I used

01:09:41.939 --> 01:09:43.299
like the Git stuff over there.

01:09:43.299 --> 01:09:45.299
And to be fair, you do use an external,

01:09:45.299 --> 01:09:47.060
like a third party, like a Git thing

01:09:47.060 --> 01:09:48.259
most of the time I would say.

01:09:48.259 --> 01:09:50.020
So I was like only RStudio.

01:09:50.020 --> 01:09:52.180
That was my little bit of Git experience.

01:09:52.180 --> 01:09:54.259
So to go from that to Positron for me

01:09:54.259 --> 01:09:56.339
was just like, it opened like floodgates.

01:09:56.339 --> 01:09:57.220
I think it's really good.

01:09:57.779 --> 01:09:59.060
I'm with Jenny on this one.

01:09:59.060 --> 01:10:01.140
I love the simplicity of RStudio's Git.

01:10:01.140 --> 01:10:02.339
And if I need anything more than that,

01:10:02.339 --> 01:10:03.140
I go to the command line.

01:10:03.140 --> 01:10:04.180
But again, divisive.

01:10:05.540 --> 01:10:07.140
For R package developers

01:10:07.140 --> 01:10:09.540
who created integrations with RStudio,

01:10:09.540 --> 01:10:10.819
will they need to learn how to build

01:10:10.819 --> 01:10:13.220
VS Code extensions or does Posit

01:10:13.220 --> 01:10:15.060
intend to offer tooling around this?

01:10:15.060 --> 01:10:15.560
We don't.

01:10:17.859 --> 01:10:18.359
Anybody?

01:10:19.939 --> 01:10:20.439
TBD.

01:10:22.660 --> 01:10:23.700
We can do that.

01:10:23.700 --> 01:10:24.200
I could talk.

01:10:25.060 --> 01:10:26.259
I could talk about that for just

01:10:27.140 --> 01:10:27.779
just a second.

01:10:27.779 --> 01:10:30.580
So Positron does implement

01:10:30.580 --> 01:10:32.419
a fairly large subset of something

01:10:32.419 --> 01:10:34.419
called the RStudio API,

01:10:34.419 --> 01:10:36.259
which is the way that R packages

01:10:36.259 --> 01:10:38.580
talk to RStudio and control it

01:10:39.220 --> 01:10:40.500
and automate it.

01:10:40.500 --> 01:10:42.180
Packages like use this and so forth.

01:10:42.819 --> 01:10:44.339
Use the RStudio API a lot.

01:10:44.339 --> 01:10:45.859
And a lot of those API calls

01:10:45.859 --> 01:10:47.060
work today in Positron.

01:10:47.859 --> 01:10:49.299
But not all of them.

01:10:49.299 --> 01:10:51.140
So there is some support.

01:10:51.140 --> 01:10:52.259
The other thing we don't currently

01:10:52.259 --> 01:10:53.859
support is RStudio add-ins.

01:10:53.859 --> 01:10:55.859
So if your package includes

01:10:55.859 --> 01:10:57.379
an RStudio add-in,

01:10:57.379 --> 01:10:58.979
that doesn't currently integrate

01:10:58.979 --> 01:11:00.180
with Positron,

01:11:00.180 --> 01:11:02.100
you know, other than the existing

01:11:02.100 --> 01:11:04.180
kind of RStudio API calls

01:11:04.180 --> 01:11:05.299
that are in the package.

01:11:05.299 --> 01:11:06.979
So those are both areas

01:11:06.979 --> 01:11:08.419
that we are working to improve.

01:11:09.939 --> 01:11:10.819
And that's support for.

01:11:10.819 --> 01:11:12.020
But as of today,

01:11:12.660 --> 01:11:14.580
what we have is a support for a

01:11:15.379 --> 01:11:17.459
limited subset of the RStudio API.

01:11:20.180 --> 01:11:21.540
Do our project files

01:11:21.540 --> 01:11:22.899
load normally in Positron?

01:11:24.819 --> 01:11:29.620
It is not used by Positron.

01:11:29.620 --> 01:11:33.540
Positron's sense of what is the space

01:11:33.540 --> 01:11:34.660
in which you are working

01:11:34.660 --> 01:11:36.180
is more about folders.

01:11:36.180 --> 01:11:38.500
So there's not an explicit file

01:11:38.500 --> 01:11:40.020
that it's looking for to say,

01:11:40.020 --> 01:11:41.700
this is my project.

01:11:41.700 --> 01:11:44.979
You can open a folder as a workspace

01:11:44.979 --> 01:11:47.140
and then you get those benefits

01:11:47.140 --> 01:11:50.740
of workspace project-based workflows.

01:11:50.740 --> 01:11:53.060
But there isn't an explicit file.

01:11:53.060 --> 01:11:54.979
We know things like here

01:11:54.979 --> 01:11:56.580
work great in Positron,

01:11:56.580 --> 01:11:59.220
depending on the specifics.

01:11:59.220 --> 01:12:00.740
I have not run into anything

01:12:00.740 --> 01:12:01.540
that had a problem

01:12:01.540 --> 01:12:02.819
with something like here.

01:12:02.819 --> 01:12:04.339
So in many ways,

01:12:04.339 --> 01:12:06.259
it's like lowered the bar

01:12:06.259 --> 01:12:09.140
for having a encapsulated,

01:12:09.140 --> 01:12:11.140
this is what I'm working on right now.

01:12:11.939 --> 01:12:14.740
So think about a workspace equaling

01:12:14.740 --> 01:12:16.339
approximately a folder,

01:12:16.339 --> 01:12:17.700
equaling approximately

01:12:18.660 --> 01:12:19.859
RStudio projects.

01:12:19.859 --> 01:12:21.060
Like they're basically all the same.

01:12:21.060 --> 01:12:22.660
And I'd say it's actually,

01:12:22.660 --> 01:12:23.859
there's less to worry about

01:12:23.859 --> 01:12:24.660
than there was before.

01:12:25.939 --> 01:12:28.580
What does the Positron logo mean?

01:12:30.819 --> 01:12:34.339
It is a P for Positron

01:12:34.339 --> 01:12:35.459
and it's a particle.

01:12:36.180 --> 01:12:40.020
And yeah, that's what we've got so far.

01:12:40.020 --> 01:12:41.060
Yeah, nothing more deep

01:12:41.060 --> 01:12:41.779
than that right now.

01:12:43.299 --> 01:12:44.979
Can we connect to existing servers

01:12:44.979 --> 01:12:46.740
via SSH from Positron?

01:12:49.779 --> 01:12:51.459
As of yesterday, yes.

01:12:52.259 --> 01:12:55.220
It is a very experimental feature.

01:12:56.020 --> 01:12:59.299
But if you, since you're all here,

01:12:59.299 --> 01:13:01.379
I can tell you there's a secret setting

01:13:01.379 --> 01:13:02.020
that we added,

01:13:02.819 --> 01:13:04.259
which is no longer going to be

01:13:04.259 --> 01:13:05.140
a secret ad for today.

01:13:05.140 --> 01:13:06.100
But there's a setting

01:13:06.819 --> 01:13:09.140
called experimental remote host.

01:13:09.140 --> 01:13:10.660
So if you go in your settings in Positron

01:13:10.660 --> 01:13:11.379
and search for that,

01:13:11.379 --> 01:13:13.779
it will allow you to connect over SSH

01:13:13.779 --> 01:13:15.299
and run R or Python

01:13:15.299 --> 01:13:16.580
on a backend Linux system.

01:13:16.819 --> 01:13:17.319
Perfect.

01:13:20.979 --> 01:13:22.660
Is there support for using

01:13:22.660 --> 01:13:23.700
Rn environments,

01:13:23.700 --> 01:13:26.259
like you can use Python virtual environments

01:13:26.259 --> 01:13:27.779
and select them from the drop down?

01:13:27.779 --> 01:13:29.060
Or is that just the interpreter?

01:13:29.700 --> 01:13:31.140
Just the interpreter for now,

01:13:31.140 --> 01:13:33.060
but there is an open issue

01:13:33.060 --> 01:13:35.540
about an enhanced kind of environments pane

01:13:35.540 --> 01:13:37.700
that gives you more UI

01:13:37.700 --> 01:13:40.500
around choosing like Rn

01:13:40.500 --> 01:13:41.540
kind of environments.

01:13:41.540 --> 01:13:44.500
Rn does work as of today

01:13:44.740 --> 01:13:46.180
but it works in much the same

01:13:46.180 --> 01:13:47.459
it works like in RStudio

01:13:47.459 --> 01:13:48.419
that you'll pop in,

01:13:48.419 --> 01:13:49.140
you'll get that,

01:13:49.700 --> 01:13:51.700
use that library of packages.

01:13:51.700 --> 01:13:53.459
If you're particularly interested in,

01:13:53.459 --> 01:13:54.419
I'd like, you know,

01:13:54.419 --> 01:13:56.740
I want to have more UI gestures

01:13:56.740 --> 01:13:58.899
around dealing with my Rn environments.

01:13:58.899 --> 01:13:59.859
There's an open issue

01:13:59.859 --> 01:14:01.540
that we'd encourage you to add any details

01:14:01.540 --> 01:14:02.259
or to thumbs up.

01:14:03.859 --> 01:14:05.859
Will it be possible to share a Positron

01:14:05.859 --> 01:14:07.220
workspace for collaboration,

01:14:07.220 --> 01:14:08.259
like with LiveShare?

01:14:11.299 --> 01:14:13.379
So LiveShare is another one of the

01:14:13.540 --> 01:14:14.500
proprietary extensions

01:14:14.500 --> 01:14:17.140
that works only with VS Code, for example.

01:14:17.140 --> 01:14:18.180
So in the future,

01:14:18.180 --> 01:14:20.259
there might be more collaborative experiences.

01:14:20.259 --> 01:14:20.979
That's, you know,

01:14:20.979 --> 01:14:22.819
a goal of what we can do with Positron.

01:14:23.700 --> 01:14:25.700
You can kind of think of in RStudio,

01:14:25.700 --> 01:14:27.379
both in Positic Cloud and Workbench,

01:14:27.379 --> 01:14:29.459
there was an idea of project sharing,

01:14:29.459 --> 01:14:31.140
which had real-time collaboration

01:14:31.140 --> 01:14:32.819
as well as directory sharing.

01:14:32.819 --> 01:14:34.979
I'd love for us to go in that direction,

01:14:34.979 --> 01:14:36.580
but that's more on like the roadmap

01:14:36.580 --> 01:14:37.620
as opposed to today.

01:14:37.859 --> 01:14:40.660
Can we run Positron in AWS EC2?

01:14:41.779 --> 01:14:44.419
Positron is a desktop IDE.

01:14:44.419 --> 01:14:46.660
You have a remote kind of SSH,

01:14:46.660 --> 01:14:48.500
the work that Jonathan was alluding to,

01:14:48.500 --> 01:14:49.459
where you can say,

01:14:49.459 --> 01:14:50.819
my ID is local,

01:14:50.819 --> 01:14:53.459
but my compute is connected to a remote server,

01:14:53.459 --> 01:14:55.620
or you can have it on Posit Workbench,

01:14:55.620 --> 01:14:58.580
which could run either on on-premise servers,

01:14:58.580 --> 01:15:01.459
AWS, Azure, Google, wherever you want.

